Failure of the right ureteropelvic junction to recanalize can result in urine backup in the kidney leading to unilateral hydronephrosis. Renal cysts may be a separate issue, pelvic kidney would mean the kidney is located in the pelvis instead of the normal position, and duplicated ureter means there are two ureters for the same kidney.

The failure of the ureteropelvic junction to recanalize is a condition known as ureteropelvic junction obstruction (UPJO), which causes urine to back up into the kidney and leads to hydronephrosis, or dilation of the renal pelvis and calyces. Therefore, the most likely finding on fetal ultrasound would be unilateral hydronephrosis. Renal cysts, pelvic kidney, or duplicated ureter may be seen on ultrasound but are not associated with UPJO.
